nemy fort can be captured, 0 is returned.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= forts.length <= 1000\n-1 <= forts[i] <= 1\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def captureForts(self, forts: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def captureForts(self, forts: List[int]) -> int:\n        max_captured = 0\n        last_fort_position = -1\n        \n        for i in range(len(forts)):\n            if forts[i] != 0:\n                if last_fort_position != -1 and forts[last_fort_position] == -forts[i]:\n                    max_captured = max(max_captured, i - last_fort_position - 1)\n                last_fort_position = i\n        \n        return max_captured\n```\n\nThis solution iterates through the `forts` list and keeps track of the position of the last encountered fort (either your fort or an empty position). When it finds another fort of the opposite type, it calculates the number of enemy forts between the two and updates the maximum number of captured forts if this number is higher.", "estimated_date": 1671321600000}